qx|A1,what is a reverse|cs|1|fp|1|cp|4|ht|a|at|^-{          What is a Reverse Bid         }
^-|cp||cs||fp||at|^b@2There are several definitions for a reverse bid. One definition is:|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


AT| 
"A reverse is a non jump bid in a suit that forces partner to take a preference to the first suit at a high level."|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


AT|

Larry Cohen describes a reverse bid as, "A non jump bid by opener at the two-level in a new suit that ranks higher than the suit opener bid first." |
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


AT|

Howard Schutzman describes a reverse bid as, "A reverse is when a player ^*Bvoluntarily^*N bypasses his first suit at the 2-level to bid a second suit. "|
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


AT|

^*BVoluntarily^*N" is an important distinction. For example in the following auction.|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


HT|k|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,,,1cp1sp!2h|at|}|ht|p|at|^b@22@H by opener is a reverse. Opener voluntarily 
bypassed clubs at the 2 level.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT| |
HT|k|cs|6|at|^o{|ia|,,,1cp1s2d!2h|at|}|ht|p|at|^o@22@H here, however, is not a reverse because the 2@C is no longer available for opener to bid if so he elects.|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


ht|r|at|^b{|ia|,,,1SP2Hp!3C|at|}|ht|r|at|^o@23@C is also a reverse. We also prefer Howard's definition as we do not have to worry about the so called "high reverse" when opener's rebid is lower ranking than his first suit, but at the three level.|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


%%%%%<<<<
ht|w|at|^b{|ia|,,,1hP2cp2s|at|}|ht|w|at|^m@2Despite the 2 over 1 bid by responder, 2@S is still a reverse. Responder must bid 3@D to return to diamonds. We have more examples next.|
