cs|1|fp|1|cp|4|ht|a|at|^-{          What is a Reverse Bid         }
^-|cp||cs||fp||ht|c|at|^b@2A reverse bid also has the following important features:|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


cs|6|AT|

{  Opener opens one of any suit (except spades).  }|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT|

{  The first suit bid is longer than the second suit bid (5+/4+ length). Some partnership may not reverse with 5-5 suits.  }|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


AT|

{  The second suit (see exception on previous page) has a higher rank than the first suit bid.  }|
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


AT|

{  It shows either a medium or maximum opener ( we will discuss it more later ).  }|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT|

{  Opener's reverse is one round forcing.  }|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

{  In 2/1 the reverse bid by opener for many experts (Mike Lawrence followers) must show extra value.  
  Many other experts including Howard Schutzman play it does not show extra values.  }|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


cp||cs||va|6|AT|

BTW, Howard says, "When responder reverses, his second suit is almost always exactly 4 cards in length. Opener may very occasionally reverse with a 5-6 hand, but they are so rare that it is reasonable for responder to assume that opener's 2nd suit is only 4 cards in length. Responder should disregard his initial assumption of a 4-card 2nd suit ^*Bonly^*N if subsequent bidding establishes the second suit as 5+ cards. There is a common misconception that, even with a balanced hand, you should reverse to show your strength. For the following reasons that is not true. |
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


ht|t|cs|6|at|^b{|ia|,,,1n|at|}|ht|w|at|^b@2With a balanced 15-17, the opening bid would
have been 1NT. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


ht|t|at|^m{|ia|,,,1DP1SP2N|at|}|ht|y|at|^m@2With a balanced 18-19, opener must rebid 2NT. Note that in this auction 2NT does not deny a 4 card major. Here, opener could easily have a 4-card heart suit." |
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


NT||
cs|1|fp|1|cp|4|ht|a|at|^-{          What is a Reverse Bid         }
^-|cp||cs||fp||ht|c|at|^b@2"So remember – a reverse always show an unbalanced hand where opener's first suit is longer than his or her second suit. The only time opener has more than 4 cards in the 2nd suit is with a very unbalanced hand (such as 5-6). Those hands are pretty rare, which is why I said opener's 2nd suit is almost always a 4-card suit. BTW, bidding 5-6 hands is a separate issue which outside the scope of this presentation."|
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

