qx|A2,How Howard Responds to a Reverse|cs|1|fp|1|cp|4|ht|a|at|^-{          How Howard responds to a Reverse Bid         }
^-|cp||cs||fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|This is the area where many partnerships, even experienced ones, have the most difficulty. Let me explain. In most auctions, one person takes charge (most often the responder), and drives the partnership to the appropriate contract. However, with reverse auctions, there is a lot of ambiguity regarding whether or not the partnership should be in game, and who is in charge. If the responder has 9+ points, then he or she needs to take charge to make sure the partnership gets to game. If the opener has a very good hand (18+), then he or she needs to take charge and make sure game is bid. However, when neither partner has game forcing values, or both partners have game forcing values, the auction can get confusing. And there is no universal agreement on how to handle this problem.|
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


AT|

At the risk of sounding immodest, I think my approach really solves the problem in most cases.  It is simple, effective, easy to understand and apply. I think if we focused on my approach, that would be best for most bridge students. I know this tutorial intends to be "fair and balanced" and present other points of view. But focusing on my approach, I think, might make things less confusing. So let tell you what I recommend.|
PG| ***** 148 ***** |


AT|

a) First of all, what are responder's obligations when opener makes a reverse bid? The simplest way to play is that it is a one round force for responder. Responder must make one more bid. Some people also play that the auction cannot stop below 2NT. That is a reasonable way to play, as it gives more flexibility in some auctions, but is not crucial.|
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


AT|
 
b) With non-game forcing values (less than 9 points), make one of the following bids (all of which are not forcing, and can be passed). 
^Ci. Show a preference for one of opener's suits. An example auction is 1@D-P-1@S-P-2@H-P-3@D. 
^Cii. Rebid responder's suit. An example auction is 1@C-P-1@S-P-2@D-P-2@S 
^Ciii. Rebid 2NT, showing at least somewhat of a stopper in the 4th suit. An example auction is 1@C-P-1@S-P-2@H-P-2NT.|
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


AT|

^Bc) With game forcing values (9 or more points): 
^Ci. Jump to game in one of opener's suits. An example auction is 1@D-P-1@S-P-2@H-P-4@H. 
^Cii. Bid 3NT with stoppers in the 4th suit. An example auction is 1@C-P-1@S-P-2@H-P-3NT. 
^Ciii. Bid the 4th suit as an artificial bid to establish a game force. An example auction is 1@C-P-1@S-P-2@D-P-2@H.|
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


NT|| 
%%%%
cs|1|fp|1|cp|4|ht|a|at|^-{          How Howard responds to a Reverse Bid         }
^-|cp||cs||fp||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|The key thing to remember is that if, as responder you have a game forcing hand, you must make a bid that communicates that to opener. The only non-game bid that is forcing is the 4th suit. If you make any other non-game bid, opener can pass. |
PG| ***** 152 ***** |


AT|

While it is true that, occasionally, bidding the 4th suit makes the auction difficult (particularly if it is a major at the 3-level), my experience is that this approach is simple, unambiguous, and works very well on most hands. It pretty much always gets you to a reasonable contract.|
