NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|The problem with reverse auctions is, often it is not clear to responder whether or not their side should be in game. Reverse bidder, me in this deal, can have as little as 16 and responder, Anna here, can have as little as 6. But I can have 18 or more, or Anna could have 10 or more. So it is difficult, without some sort of agreements, to decide whether or not to be in game. |
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Ingberman convention tries to solve the problem as follows. If responder bids 2N (as a relay), Reverse bidder is required to bid 3@C with a minimum reverse hand (16-bad 18). After bids 3@C by Reverse bidder, responder is responsible for placing the contract.|
PG| ***** 160 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|There are a lot of problems with that approach in my opinion. So I suggest you adopt the approach I play, which I think makes bidding much easier. There are no "relays" in my approach.|
PG| ***** 161 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|If responder has a game forcing hand, she bids 4th Suit Forcing. In this case for example, if Anna decided she had a game force she could bid 2@H (4th Suit) to establish a game force. Any other bid by Anna does not establish a game force, and is assumed by Reverse bidder to show less than a game force. Then the Reverse bidder is in charge to set the contract.|
PG| ***** 162 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|I do have another rule to give the auction a little more flexibility. That rule is that the partnership cannot stop below 2N. So if Anna bids, for example, 2@S over 2@D, she is not establishing a game force, but it is still forcing because her bid is below 2N. |
PG| ***** 163 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Again the two rules for responder, when her/his had is stronger than a minimum, are:
a) 4th Suit establishes a game force
b) the partnership cannot stop below 2N.|
PG| ***** 164 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|Other than 4th Suit, in my system, all other bids are natural. If Anna bids anything else (say 3@C or 3@D) that shows less than a game force. Note the 3@C and 3@D are above 2N. 2@S would show 5 spades. |
PG| ***** 165 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BHoward: ^*N|cp||at|If Anna does not establish a game force, then opener, with 18+, becomes captain and is responsible for getting to game. In effect 2N becomes responder's "minimum" second bid instead of an Ingberman relay and it should show a stopper in the unbid suit.|
